            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kai Zhang is a product of deliberate design, both in his career and in his upbringing. The only son of Chinese immigrants who settled in Cupertino, his childhood was a structured process of academic excellence and quiet expectation. His father, a hardware engineer, and his mother, a math tutor, viewed a STEM education not as an option, but as a roadmap to stability. Kai followed it dutifully, earning an undergraduate degree in chemical engineering before pursuing a Master\u2019s in Materials Science at UC Berkeley. This move to the Bay Area felt like both a graduation and a homecoming to the epicenter of his parents\u2019 ambitions for him.\n\nHe landed a coveted role as a Process Engineer at a burgeoning battery technology company. For years, his life was a predictable commute to a South Bay campus, optimizing fabrication lines and refining chemical deposition techniques. He was good at it, finding a certain satisfaction in improving a system\u2019s efficiency by a fraction of a percent. The turning point was the pandemic. His company went fully remote, and Kai\u2019s 0.0-mile commute became permanent. Suddenly untethered from the office, the clean, logical lines of his life began to blur.\n\nNow 34, Kai lives alone in a minimalist one-bedroom apartment in the Inner Richmond. His days are a quiet hum of virtual meetings and data analysis, the window beside his desk often filled with fog rolling in from the nearby Presidio. The solitude, compounded by a relationship that ended a year ago, pushed him to seek a more tactile connection to the world. He found it in a community ceramics studio a few blocks away.\n\nThree nights a week, Kai trades his keyboard for a potter\u2019s wheel. The unpredictable nature of clay\u2014its tendency to crack, warp, and slump\u2014is a therapeutic counterpoint to the rigid certainties of his job. His connection to San Francisco is not found in downtown happy hours, but in the quiet ritual of walking to his studio, grabbing dumplings on Clement Street, and feeling the city\u2019s creative undercurrent. His hope is no longer about climbing the corporate ladder, but about saving enough to one day open a small studio of his own\u2014a space where he can perfect a different kind of process, one driven by art instead of algorithms."
